  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n- Provides 40 recommendations for countries to implement\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides standards for financial transparency and reporting\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets international banking standards for money laundering prevention\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish consistent AML regulations across EU member states\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act/USA PATRIOT Act (United States)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\nThese frameworks generally require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Implement reporting requirements\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Establish financial intelligence units\n- Collaborate internationally on investigations\n\nMost developed countries have implemented national laws consistent with these international standards.",
